climbs.name: Laughing Gas
climbs.fa: Paul DuVall and Kevin Dorsman late 90's

content.description: Fun climbing with thin crux in the middle. 11 bolts.
content.location: NE arête of Incisor. Left-hand side when viewed from the end of the trail.

climbs.name: Kamps-Gill route (Original route)
climbs.fa: Bob Kamps and John Gill, Aug 19, 1961

content.description: Begin in rotten cracks on the west edge of the southwest toe, climb the cracks placing suspect pro. From the cracks gain large crystals and get established below water groove. Execute some hard and bold moves up to easier and slightly more protectable climbing. (Pretty big ground fall potential if you blow the crux.)

climbs.name: Flouride Treatment
climbs.fa: Paul Duvall, Jenny Collins and Kevin Dorsman late 90's

content.description: Follow the bolt line to anchors.  I remember it being a fun climb, but haven't been back on it in about 20 years. I walked by it the other day and will need to get back on it in order to write a better description and post a photo.
content.location: Bolt Line on South Face (Spire 9 to your back).

content.description: Steep, well protected climbing with a thin crux mid height.
content.location: West face of Incisor. Right of 'pearly whites' .11

content.description: The Incisor is a large blocky rock about 100 feet high.  This rock has old trad routes, new bolted routes, and boulder problems on it.  The trad routes include an old Royal Robbins route, and a John Gill route.  Three bolted routes can be found that are probably in the range of 5.10 to 5.11.  Also, several boulder problems exist on the northwest face of the rock.  Look for about a half dozen old Gill that lead to a small ledge about 15 feet up next to a piton.
